<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Western Transvaal `Tense'; AWB Activity Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Western Transvaal `Tense'; AWB Activity Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2904204094 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in Afrikaans 
1800 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2904204094 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>
<F P=105>  Afrikaans </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Western Transvaal was tense today, but no serious 
incidents occurred since 14 magisterial districts were declared 
unrest areas. There were earlier reports of AWB [Afrikaner 
Resistance Movement] gatherings in this area and Robbie 
Terblanche went to investigate. 
  [Begin Terblanche recording] Everything seemed normal, and 
no 
serious incidents had been reported. Tension could be felt 
wherever we spoke to people, and nobody was prepared to appear 
on camera. There was a strong army and police presence. Several 
road blocks were set up. According to the police liaison 
officer for Western Transvaal, Captain Koos Degenaar, the step 
to declare 14 magisterial districts unrest areas was taken 
mainly to prevent unrest, conflict, and violence. We received a 
report that AWB members had gathered in the Koster region but we 
could not confirm this during our visit. Our investigation at 
Koster led to cameraman Roy Freeman and myself being stopped by 
police between Koster and Lichtenburg and escorted to the 
Lichtenburg police station. They wanted to confiscate our video 
material but they released us after viewing the material. 
According to the police people are very tense and they are 
receiving several calls from concerned people. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

