<H3> <TI>   International Community Reaction to Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    International Community Reaction to Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Tanzanian President Commends Elections </H4>

<F P=102> AB0205064494 Paris AFP in English 1449 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0205064494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Dar es Salaam, April 30 (AFP) -- Tanzanian President 
Ali Hassan Mwinyi praised South Africans for successfully 
conducting their first democratic elections ever, and urged them 
maintain peace after the polls, officials said Saturday [30 
April]. 
  "It is only through reconciliation that the people of South 
Africa can be able to build a new, peaceful and progressive 
country," Mwinyi said in a statement to the media. 
  Mwinyi said the whole world was satisfied with last week's 
historic elections, which ended centuries of white minority in 
South Africa. 
  Tanzania was a strident critic of South Africa's apartheid 
policy which disenfranched the majority black community. 
  Mwinyi pledged to cooperate with whatever government comes 
to 
power after the elections results are declared. 

</TEXT>

