<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Agreement Reached in Lusaka; U.S. Envoy Expected </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No Agreement Reached in Lusaka; U.S. Envoy Expected </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0305205894 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0305205894 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Alves Antonio in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] Good evening. The Angolan peace talks being held in 
Lusaka were unproductive today. The government and National 
Union for the Total Independence of Angola [UNITA] negotiators 
did not achieve anything. They are staying put on the 
modalities for the implementation of the second round of 
presidential elections. The mediators presented a new version, 
which the government and UNITA negotiating teams assessed this 
afternoon. Blondin Beye is doing everything to dissipate doubts 
and overcome the differences. So far that has not been easy. 
The next hours may be decisive. 
  Meanwhile, a source close to the talks told our reporters 
here that Paul Hare, U.S. president's special envoy to Angola's 
peace negotiations, leaves Lusaka for Luanda tomorrow, where he 
will within the next few days meet with His Excellency Engineer 
Jose Eduardo dos Santos, president of the Republic. It is 
presumed that the U.S. diplomat will report to President dos 
Santos on the results of talks held recently by the U.S. 
Administration and Congress in Washington. It has been reported 
in Lusaka that Ambassador Hare is presently on a diplomatic tour 
that may have some impact on the government-UNITA talks. Our 
reporters have also learned from reliable source says that U.S. 
Senator Paul Simon is scheduled to visit Angola this month, 
having expressed in Washington the wish to meet with the Angolan 
head of state, Jose Eduardo dos Santos and UNITA leader Jonas 
Savimbi. 

</TEXT>

