<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Requests Postponement of CSC Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Requests Postponement of CSC Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0405080494 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
0600 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0405080494 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yesterday, the Mozambican Government asked for a 
meeting of the Supervision and Control Commission, CSC, to be 
postponed. That meeting was supposed to discuss the 
disappearance of more than 12,000 Mozambique Armed Forces, FAM, 
soldiers, according to estimates presented by the UN Operations 
in Mozambique, Unomoz. 
  Aldo Ajello, the UN secretary general's representative in 
Mozambique, has said in Maputo that the Mozambican Government 
delegation to the CSC has asked for a postponement to study the 
report and the number of soldiers said to be missing. The 
government had initially handed in to the Cease-Fire Commission, 
CCF, a list of 76,000 soldiers but then, without any 
explanation, that figure came down to 64,000 men. 
  Labor Minister Teodato Hunguana, the second man in the 
government team to the CSC, had said in mid-April that the 
figures produced by the government were viable and that Unomoz 
was using outdated information. Observers in the Mozambican 
capital admit the possibility that the Mozambican (?Defense 
Ministry) could have submitted lists containing false or 
outdated information, including soldiers killed or missing in 
action, as well as deserters. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

