<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Counting Said Nearly Complete </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Counting Said Nearly Complete </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0405065794 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in English 0600 
GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0405065794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] No election results have been announced since 
yesterday evening, but they should begin flowing again this 
morning. The IEC [Independent Electoral Commission] decided to 
revise its counting procedures last night, and instead of 
entering batches of votes into the computer as they come in, 
they are now entering the total number of votes at counting 
stations. 
  IEC spokesman Pieter Cronje says the vote counting is 
complete in all regions except the PWV [Pretoria, Witwatersrand, 
Vereeniging] and KwaZulu/Natal, and that more than 50 percent of 
the votes in KwaZulu/Natal have been counted. He said the final 
allocations of seats in the National Assembly and the provincial 
legislatures and a ruling on whether the election was free and 
fair could be expected late tomorrow afternoon. 
  The last results showed that with just over 53 percent of 
the 
votes counted the ANC had 62.5 percent compared with 22 percent 
for the NP [National Party], and 8.3 percent for the IFP 
[Inkatha Freedom Party]. The Freedom Front has 3 percent, 
followed by the DP [Democratic Party] with 1.7 percent, and the 
PAC [Pan-Africanist Congress] with 1.3. 

</TEXT>

