<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   ANC: `Large-Scale' Voting Irregularities in Natal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ANC: `Large-Scale' Voting Irregularities in Natal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0305191794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1856 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0305191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Durban May 3 SAPA -- The African National Congress 
Midlands region in KwaZulu/Natal on Tuesday [3 May] claimed 
large-scale voting irregularities, particularly in areas north 
of the Tugela River. "We are obviously concerned and anxious 
about this lead (in election results in the province by the 
Inkatha Freedom Party [IFP]). We are convinced there has been 
massive irregularities," said ANC spokesman Dr Blade Nzimande. 
  The IFP's Dr Ziba Jiyane earlier predicted a 60 per cent 
majority for his party, adding that the IFP had overwhelming 
support north of the Tugela River. "This lead is not a true 
reflection of the IFP's popularity," Dr Nzimande said. 
  On Tuesday afternoon an Independent Electoral Commission 
[IEC] report gave the IFP a lead of 21.4 per cent over its ANC 
rival. Dr Nzimande said the three ANC Natal regions were 
meeting to discuss "this grave situation". 
  Discrepancies were noted in votes cast, particularly in 
KwaZulu- administrated areas, and had been forwarded to the IEC 
for investigation, he said. He said even in rural areas, where 
the ANC had a marginal support base, "it doesn't reflect at all". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

