<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arms Suppliers Bid To Sell Attack Helicopters to UK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Arms Suppliers Bid To Sell Attack Helicopters to UK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0305205294 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in English 1800 
GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0305205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] South African arms suppliers are making a bid to 
sell attack helicopters to Britain. They have been invited to 
submit a tender to supply Britain's Royal Air Force with 
Rooivalk [red falcon] choppers, a signal that the arms embargo 
may soon be lifted. Marinus Wijnbeek reports: 
  After about 20 years the second South African Air Force 
flight to Britain, in as many weeks, is preparing to leave from 
Waterkloof Air Force base, and in its hold is Denel's Rooivalk 
attack helicopter. Fitting the large aircraft into Hercules is 
an engineering feat all by itself. Rooivalk will be 
demonstrated at the coming air show at (Middlewallop) in 
Britain. Since December last year the weapons systems have 
undergone intensive tests. The aircraft has a chin- mounted 
canon and it is also fitted with the Kentron ZT-3 antitank 
missile. It is these tank killing properties and its very 
modern technology that resulted in the invitation to submit the 
bid in Britain. The aircraft can operate under all weather 
conditions in virtually any region of the world. Six other 
contenders from the USA and Europe have also entered 
helicopters. If successful 91 Rooivalk aircraft will be 
exported to the UK. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

