<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Number of Seats for Each Party Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Number of Seats for Each Party Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0505074394 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 0600 GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0505074394 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] With just over 66 percent of the provisional 
national votes now known, the ANC will be the dominating party 
in the National Assembly with 251 seats, compared with the NP 
[National Party] with 88, the IFP [Inkatha Freedom Party] with 
34, and the Freedom Front [FF] with 11 seats. The DP 
[Democratic Party] should have seven seats, the PAC 
[Pan-Africanist Congress] six, the African Christian Democratic 
Party [ACDP] two, and the African Moderates Congress Party 
[AMCP] one seat. This means that eight parties could take their 
seats in the National Assembly. Until now none of the other 
smaller parties has obtained enough support for a seat in the 
assembly. According to the latest provisional results the ANC 
has 64.8 percent of the national vote, compared with the NP's 
20.5 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

