<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   ANC Denies Withdrawal of Fraud Charges Against IFP </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ANC Denies Withdrawal of Fraud Charges Against IFP </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0405161494 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1605 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0405161494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg May 4 SAPA -- The African National 
Congress on Wednesday [4 May] night strongly denied it had 
withdrawn charges of electoral fraud against the Inkatha Freedom 
Party [IFP] in KwaZulu/Natal. 
  The organisation's secretary general, Mr Cyril Ramaphosa, 
issued the denial barely two hours after IFP leader Chief 
Mangosuthu Buthelezi said he had learnt that the ANC had 
withdrawn these charges. Stressing the anc's commitment to 
accept the results of a free and fair election, Mr Ramaphosa 
said his organisation had presented new evidence of irregularity 
to the Independent Electoral Commission (IEC). "The ANC has new 
evidence that it has submitted to the IEC, further strengthening 
its case on the irregularities in KwaZulu/Natal. It is the firm 
hope of the ANC that outstanding problems contributing to the 
delay in counting will be speedily resolved to allow the country 
to embark on the many tasks awaiting the government of national 
unity." 
  Earlier, IEC spokesman Mr Glenn McDougall confirmed the 
commission had found no evidence of extensive voting fraud in 
KwaZulu/Natal, as claimed by the ANC. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

