<H3> <TI>   International Reaction to Elections, Mandela Victory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    International Reaction to Elections, Mandela Victory </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Russian Foreign Ministry Hails Results </H4>

<F P=102> LD0405160894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1352 
GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405160894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 4 May -- The Russian Federation's Foreign 
Ministry expressed its willingness to cooperate with the new 
democratic South Africa. A statement issued by the foreign 
policy department voiced the hope that the good relations that 
have taken shape between the two countries and their peoples 
"will, in the period that lies ahead, be further developed in 
the interests of world peace and prosperity." 
  In the opinion of the Russian Foreign Ministry, history's 
first general election in the South Africa is an event "that has 
fundamentally altered the course of historical development of 
that country and of the region as a whole." 
  "The international community, which has for decades sought 
persistently to bring about a restoration of racial and social 
justice in South Africa, notes today that that goal has been 
attained. For its part, Russia, which has invariably backed all 
constructive efforts by the government, parties, and public 
organizations in South Africa along the road of democratic 
transformation, shares with everyone a sense of profound 
satisfaction with the results of those efforts," the Foreign 
Ministry statement stresses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

