<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Famrers Union Chief Reacts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Famrers Union Chief Reacts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0505131294 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 1100 GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0505131294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The president of the Transvaal Agricultural Union, 
Mr., Dries Bruwer, says a new government should have talks with 
organized agriculture before completing an agricultural and land 
policy for South Africa. Mr. Bruwer was reacting to the ANC's 
land policy announcement yesterday in which sweeping land 
reforms were envisaged. Mr. Bruwer said land claims and demands 
had always been a sensitive matter and should be approached with 
great circumspection because of their conflict potential. He 
said a government which did not take cultural differences into 
account could destabilize a country. Referring to land demands 
after forced settlement, Mr. Bruwer said the ANC should not 
forget that large numbers of white farmers had also been 
resettled. He said traditional land ownership applied to white 
farmers in the same way as it did to the other five ethnic 
groups in the Northern Transvaal. 

</TEXT>

