<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Report Urges Swifter Demobilization of Troops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Report Urges Swifter Demobilization of Troops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0505083694 Maputo Radio Mozambique Network in Portuguese 
0500 GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0505083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Mozambique Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to a report UN Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali has submitted to the UN Security Council for its 
consideration, some 17,000 government and Mozambique National 
Resistance, Renamo, soldiers must be demobilized from the 
centers where they are serving at this stage. Such centers 
include hospital, air, and naval bases, as well as barracks. 
  The report presented to the UN Security Council says that 
soldiers have had to stay in their assembly areas for long 
periods because of demobilization delays. The UN secretary 
general's report also mentions delays in the scrapping of some 
155,000 militia and other (?paramilitary) forces, and it adds 
that a lack of air transportation helped paralyze that process 
in March, though half of the weapons declared by the government, 
in the hands of the paramilitary forces, had been collected in 
April. 

</TEXT>

