<H3> <TI>   CSC Meeting Postponement Termed `Nothing Dramatic' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CSC Meeting Postponement Termed `Nothing Dramatic' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0405124194 Maputo Radio Mozambique Network in Portuguese 
1030 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0405124194 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Mozambique Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Labor Minister Teodato Hunguana told Radio 
Mozambique in Maputo today that there is nothing dramatic 
threatening the Mozambican peace process. Minister Hunguana was 
reacting to speculation concerning the Mozambican Government's 
successive requests to postpone the Supervision and Control 
Commission [CSC] meeting to analyze a report by UN Special 
Representative Aldo Ajello. 
  Minister Hunguana described the report as extensive, adding 
it presents many problems that require action, rather than a 
formal response. He noted that the government has been working 
to present the CSC with concrete details concerning the schedule 
to be followed up to the holding of elections in October. 
  Meanwhile, Radio Mozambique has learned that the CSC is 
scheduled to meet in Maputo tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

