<H3> <TI>   CSC Receives 12 Reports of Cease-Fire Violations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CSC Receives 12 Reports of Cease-Fire Violations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0505131494 Maputo Radio Mozambique Network in Portuguese 
1030 GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0505131494 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Mozambique Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The Supervision and Control Commission, CSC, has 
received 12 notifications of alleged cease-fire violations. 
Eight of those came from the government and the other four from 
the Mozambique National Resistance, Renamo. A total of (?10) of 
those reports have already been investigated. Only two must 
still be investigated. 
  In his report to the UN Security Council, UN Secretary 
General said that neither the government nor Renamo have allowed 
the UN Operations in Mozambique, Unomoz, access to certain 
military bases. His report also noted that neither side has 
supplied full military equipment lists yet. Butrus Butrus-Ghali 
also noted in his report that some government assembly areas are 
too full while others are virtually empty. [passage omitted] 
  In his report, the UN secretary general also said that by 18 
April Renamo had demobilized 3 percent of all its listed forces 
in the assembly areas, while the government had released 28 
percent of its men. 

</TEXT>

