<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Gabon </F>
<H3> <TI>   Oil Workers' Strike Causes Shortage; Flights Suspended </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Oil Workers' Strike Causes Shortage; Flights Suspended </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0405185494 Libreville RTG Chaine Nationale Radio Network 
in French 1200 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB0405185494 </F>
<F P=104>  Libreville RTG Chaine Nationale Radio Network 
in French 1200 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A meeting has been taking place since this morning 
at the Gabonese Trade Union Confederation headquarters between 
Mines and Fuel Minister Paul Toungui and representatives of the 
various petroleum companies. The meeting follows the extension 
of the 48-hour warning strike launched by the workers of the 
Libreville Petroleum Group. This strike first resulted in a gas 
shortage and now a fuel shortage which has caused a lot of 
inconvenience for housewives and many drivers who could not get 
to work this morning. The petroleum workers, who are threatening 
to extend their strike to 8 May, are demanding a 15-percent 
salary increase. 
  [Paris AFP in French at 1158 GMT on 4 May in a similar 
Libreville-datelined report adds: "A two-day strike by workers 
of petroleum products distribution companies has today led to 
the suspension of domestic flights and a fuel and gas shortage 
in Libreville. All domestic flights will be suspended until 8 
May unless a solution is found between now and then, airline 
sources say. However, national Air Gabon Airlines are 
maintaining international flights. Gas stations have not 
received supplies since 2 May and a lot of them, even though 
pump attendants are not participating in the strike, have had to 
stop distributing fuel. It is also impossible to find gas 
cylinders, which are distributed by the petroleum companies."] 

</TEXT>

