<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   Planning Minister Appeals for International Force </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Planning Minister Appeals for International Force </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405144794 Paris Radio France International in French 1230 
GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] There has been a new upsurge of tension in 
Rwanda. Yesterday evening three UNAMIR [UN Aid Mission in 
Rwanda] soldiers were injured during shelling of the airport, 
and seven Rwandans were also injured as the UN attempted to 
evacuate them from a hotel in the town center. [passage omitted] 
  In neighboring Tanzania, since yesterday the UN special 
representative has been stepping up his informal talks with the 
warring sides. Jacques-Roger Booh-Booh was due to go to Kampala 
this morning to meet the Ugandan president and then return to 
Arusha. The Rwandan Patriotic Front, RPF, for its part has 
already described any possible intervention by foreign troops in 
Rwanda as too late and pointless, because, the RPF says, the 
genocide has already been committed. This is a view which is 
not shared by the planning minister of the interim government. 
Speaking on a stopover in Dakar, he called for rapid 
intervention by a foreign force. Augustin Ngirabatware was 
speaking to Nicolas Balique: 
  [Begin Ngirabatware recording] I am issuing an appeal to the 
international community to help the people. We also expect the 
international community to use its powers of persuasion with the 
RPF to make it understand that only a peaceful solution will 
allow Rwandans to live together. Third, this international 
force -- which should be neutral but very effective -- should be 
deployed in Rwanda as rapidly as possible -- this is extremely 
urgent -- in order to help the government and the RPF to 
maintain the cease-fire, and to permit the negotiations to begin 
again; and speaking about a neutral, effective international 
force, the Rwandan Government does not rule out any country, but 
we believe that in any case, as far as any direct or indirect 
involvement is concerned, the official armed forces of Uganda 
should not participate in it, and the Burundi Army should not 
participate in it. As far as the Belgian Army is concerned, I 
believe that Belgium has already decided not to take part in 
this kind of force in Rwanda. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

