Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Consensus on Presidential Elections Expected Soon </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Consensus on Presidential Elections Expected Soon </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0405195294 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0405195294 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Government and UNITA [National Union for the Total 
Independence of Angola] negotiators have met to try to narrow 
their differences and deal once and for all with the modalities 
for the second round of presidential elections. No plausible 
and conclusive progress was made at this afternoon's meeting. 
The two negotiating teams will return tomorrow to the 
Mulungushi International Conference Center for direct talks to 
try to resolve the differences. Consensus is expected to be 
reached tomorrow. This evening the two delegations will try to 
improve on their ideas. Should this happen, the talks will only 
need to deal with national reconciliation issues. 
  An official source has told us that Blondin Beye leaves 
Lusaka for South Africa tomorrow to attend president-elect 
Nelson Mandela's inauguration. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

